{
  "texts": [
    "Frequently, data scientists must make trade-offs between the quantity of data that can be harmonized and the precision with which the harmonized data operationalizes the desired underlying concepts 69, [106] [107] [108] [109].",
    "Torres-Espin and Ferguson articulate this idea as the harmonization-information tradeoff 51 which states that \"the level of granularity in harmonizing data determines the amount of information lost. \"",
    "While they focus specifically on biomedical data in their analysis, their insights can be broadly applicable to harmonization across fields.",
    "Factors which affect this tradeoff include the (i) availability of of timely and relevant data (a particular issue in fields without established norms for data sharing) (ii) the quality of data collected (a particular issue when data collection methodology is not transparent or accessible) (iii) and the comparability, and therefore the ultimate potential for harmonizing the underlying data (common across all fields).",
    "To illustrate these tradeoffs through COVID-19 school restriction policies, note the OxCGRT dataset 33 uses an ordinal variables to capture this information as follows:"
  ]
}